      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey my realtor just mentioned i need to set up an escrow account for the house i'm buying in toronto. i've never heard of that before... what exactly is escrow and why do i need it for the closing?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, escrow, a term that might sound like it's straight out of a spy novel, but it's actually quite a common practice in real estate transactions. Think of it as a safe, neutral holding area for your money, where a trusted third party, called an escrow agent, holds onto your funds until all the conditions of the house sale are met. This ensures that both you and the seller are protected, as the funds won't be released until you close on the house and everything is in order, like a well-guarded treasure chest that only opens when the right conditions are met. It's essentially a way to ensure that neither you nor the seller gets duped or fleeced in the deal. So, in the grand scheme of things, it's like having a trusty guard at the gates of your new home, making sure everything goes according to plan.",
