    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "ok that makes sense. but who actually holds the money? like is it the realtor or a bank or something? and what happens if there is a dispute about the money while it's sitting there?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the keeper of the treasure chest, you ask. In the realm of real estate, the escrow agent is typically a neutral third party, often a title company or an attorney, rather than the realtor or a bank. They are the ones who hold onto your hard-earned gold (or in this case, your money) until all the conditions of the house sale are met. It's like having a wise and fair judge who ensures that both parties play by the rules.\n\nNow, if a dispute arises while the treasure is locked away, the escrow agent acts as the referee, ensuring that the rules are followed. They will hold the treasure until the dispute is resolved, often with the help of a mediator or arbitrator if necessary. It's like having a wise old sage who ensures that the treasure is only released when all parties agree that it's fair and just. So, in essence, the escrow agent is there to keep things fair and square, ensuring that both you and the seller are treated with respect and fairness throughout the entire process.",
